Abhinav Kumar (University of Massachusetts, Amherst)

knitr::include_graphics('./Copper Trade Network (2012 - 2021).png')

Introduction

This study has been designed to explore the trade relations that have developed over 10 years from 2012 to 2021 for top producers of Copper, Lithium, and Graphite. These commodities have been selected to study how has the battery and electric international trade economy evolved. The data has been extracted using UN Comtrade API. The data extraction code will be attached separately. There are many restrictions while extracting data from UN Comtrade website. In a day only 50000 hits are allowed. The export or import data can be extracted for one country at a time. We cannot extracted trade data for multiple countries at one time. This is a restriction imposed by the API. In case more than 50000 hits are required per day, then license needs to be procured from UN Comtrade. As the data is required only for academic study purposes, the extraction has been limited to 50000 only. However, in order to extract the data, multiple runs and iterations had to be made over a period of four days.

The commodities for the study have been selected using international Harmonized System (HS) codes for trade. The commodities selected are in the input form rather than value added finished products form to understand the production pattern of producers and consumption pattern of importers. The HS codes selected are as below:

  1. Copper - 2603, 7406, 7404
  2. Lithium - 283691, 282520
  3. Graphite - 3801, 2504

In the data set we have the details of exports and imports trade values in USD for the three commodities. For the sake of this initial study, we will only look at one commodity to to develop an understanding. In future, all the commodities will be used to understand the overall trade scenario. Although, we have extracted at least two HS codes across the three commodities, for the purpose of the study, various classes/type of the same commodity will be treated as one. Like copper has three HS codes and for purpose of this study all the three HS codes will be treated as copper.

library(readr)

trade <- read_csv(file.choose())



trade_copper <- trade %>% filter(commodity_code == "2603" | commodity_code == "7406" | commodity_code == "7404")
hide 
# Converting all Imports to Exports by interchanging the reporter and partner



trade_copper %>%

  filter(trade_flow == "Import") %>%

  mutate(aux = reporter, reporter = partner, partner = aux,

         trade_flow = "Export") %>%

  select(-aux) -> tmp

rbind(trade_copper, tmp) %>%

  filter(trade_flow == "Export") -> total_trade_clean



total_trade_clean <- total_trade_clean[, -c(3,5)] #removing reporter_iso and partner_iso columns



head(total_trade_clean)

# creating igraph network



X <- data.frame("From" = total_trade_clean$reporter,

                "To" = total_trade_clean$partner,

                "weight" = total_trade_clean$trade_value_usd)



net.ig <- graph.data.frame(X, directed = TRUE)

E(net.ig)$weight <- total_trade_clean$trade_value_usd



adj <- get.adjacency(net.ig, sparse = FALSE)



summary(net.ig)

# Coercing igraph object to statnet object



network <- intergraph::asNetwork(net.ig)



# plotting the copper export network

set.seed(007)

plot(network,  main = "Copper Trade Network (2012 - 2021)")

Network Structure

The edgelist consists of 205 nodes and 10244 ties. The weight of the edges is the value of trade in USD that is being generated due to exports of copper from one nation to other. The edgelist is directed one as exports is unidirectional from one nation to the other.

hide 
print(paste0("The number of vertices in the network is:",vcount(net.ig)))


[1] "The number of vertices in the network is:205"
hide 
print(paste0("The number of edges in the network is:",ecount(net.ig)))


[1] "The number of edges in the network is:10244"

Network Exploration basis time interval (years)

Here, ten years time span has been broken down into 3 intervals. From 2012 to 2014 time interval we can observe that 191 countries exported copper 3217 times to importing nations. From 2015 to 2017, the export activity dipped in terms of number of nations exporting copper to 175 and the number of trades dropped to 3074. However, from 2018 to 2021 the number of exporting nations increased to 185 (although less than 2012 - 14 time interval) with number of trades reported as 3953 irrespective of the COVID scenario. This gives the hint that focus in the electric and battery sector has increased over time.

#calculating reciprocity

reciprocity(net.ig)


[1] 0.6163485

The minimal structural element in a social network is a dyad. The complete trade network can be broken down into constitutent parts. These parts are called motifs. A motif has two nodes that is called a dyad. In a dyad, both the members have good bargaining power. There are 413 mutually directed relationships among pair of countries trading copper over 10 years time frame.

The reciprocity is about 62%, which shows the chance with which the nations are trading. This confirms that these pair of countries are exporting and importing copper. So the producer nations (ego) efforts are reciprocated by the importer nations (alters). There are 366 countries that have just exported copper without any imports from the countries in the given sample. There are 20131 pair of countries with no trade relationships. These asymmetric dyads reflect a hierarchy in terms of exporting countries.

hide 
# exploring triad census

triad.census(network)


         003   012   102 021D 021U 021C  111D 111U 030T 030C   201

[1,] 1308003 29844 27302 1343 6604 2376 15886 6675    9    5 15408

     120D 120U 120C 210 300

[1,]  160   24  125 587 559

Triads consist of three nodes and are more complex than dyads. Here we can observe 16 isomorphic classes of triads. As per triad census, there are 1308003 empty triads. These nations a part of null triad are not having any trade relations. 1343 triads and 6604 triads are vacuously transitive. There is a chance that the trading nations in these triads might make it a complete triplet by trading between the two nations that are not trading as of now. Total of 9 perfectly transitive triads exist in the network that are trading copper among themselves. A total of 743 closed transitive tralds exists in the network among trading nations.

hide 
is_directed(net.ig)


[1] TRUE
hide 
is_weighted(net.ig)


[1] TRUE
hide 
is_bipartite(net.ig)


[1] FALSE

The network developed is directed due the nature of trade i.e.export and the network is weighted with with the export trade value in USD.

The Global transitivity of the network is 8.6%, which is the overall proportion of triads among all connected triads. So there is 8.6% chance in the trade network that a nation will trade copper with another nation across all connected triplets. The average transitivity is 0.95, which is the transitivity of the local triad clusters, i.e.the ratio of local triangles to all connected triangles. The unconnected triples here give an idea that there are possibilities of brokerage.

hide

[1] 0.08362588
hide 
#get average local clustering coefficient: igraph

transitivity(net.ig, type="average")


[1] 0.9476711

Path Lengths

The average path length in the weighted trade network is 171196.8. Here, we can explore the distance travelled between two trading nations. For this study purpose we have taken India and China as the trading nations. Using distances function we calculate the geodesic distance (the shortest path distance between India and china). The distance between India and China is 11. Te shortest path between the two nations involves 4 nodes.

Density

Density of a network is the ratio of the number of edges and the number of possible edges. Here we can observe that the trade network density with and without the loop is almost same resulting to 0.24. Now as this network has multiple edges, the trade network density cannot be interpreted clearly as density is ill-defined.

hide 
graph.density(net.ig)


[1] 0.2449546
hide 
graph.density(net.ig, loops=TRUE)


[1] 0.2437597

Degree

Degree of a node is equal to the number of incoming and outgoing links it has. The degree measures the node centrality or a popularity of a node. In this case degree represents the number of trade linkages a country has. In the trade network Germany has the highest number of overall trade (exports and imports) links followed by China and USA. In order to further understand the degree attribute at country level, a new data frame trade.nodes is being prepared to explore and analyze. In the rest of the section of this study we will analyze various network parameters. In order to do so, all the parameters will be stored in a data frame trade.nodes. From trade.nodes, we can observe that Germany, and USA have high number of exports linkage given the out degree parameter is very high among all nations.

Centrality and Centralization

The centrality of a node is a measure of prominence of the node relative to other nodes in the network. In the trade network we will analyze various types of centrality measures for the exporting nations and analyze the most central nation in the overall network. Centralization is a property of overall graph. It compares the most central node to the other nodes in the network. The inward centralization score for the trade network in this case for the given sample is 8.44 which is more than the export centralization score which is 7.12. This is in sync with our analysis as we have take export data of top copper producing nations and the trade network is expected to have more inward transactions as the handful of nations are exporting to the world. However, interestingly these handful nations are also importing copper from much smaller producers such as Eritrea, Rawanda, Sudan, etc. in very small loads. While Germany has the highest degree linkage in the overall trade network, its imports are more than the exports. However, these are just the links and not the amount of trade information. Basis the eigenvalue centrality measure, that determines how important the neighborhood of the nodes is in the network are and higher the eigenvalue centrality, the more important the neighbors of that node are with respect to other nodes in the network. We can infer from the centrality dataframe below that Russian Federation has the highest eigenvalue centrality. Hence, Russian Federation could be the most influential trading nation in the network. Then, derived and reflected Eigenvector centrality has been computed to better understand whether the influence is more observed in the neighborhood of the nodes or is it more observed on the strength of the node itself

Derived and Reflected Centrality

In order to claculate the centralities, we are creating here adjacency matrix to do rest of the analysis.

hide 
matrix <- as.matrix(as_adjacency_matrix(net.ig, attr = "weight"))



#square the adjacency matrix

matsq<-t(matrix) %*% matrix



#Calculate the proportion of reflected centrality.

trade.nodes$rc<-diag(matsq)/rowSums(matsq)



#replace missing values with 0

trade.nodes$rc<-ifelse(is.nan(trade.nodes$rc),0,trade.nodes$rc)



#Calculate received eigenvalue centrality

trade.nodes$eigen.rc<-trade.nodes$eigen*trade.nodes$rc



#Calculate the proportion of derived centrality.

trade.nodes$dc<-1-diag(matsq)/rowSums(matsq)



#replace missing values with 0

trade.nodes$dc<-ifelse(is.nan(trade.nodes$dc),1,trade.nodes$dc)



#Calculate received eigenvalue centrality

trade.nodes$eigen.dc<-trade.nodes$eigen*trade.nodes$dc

Network Brokerage

Brokerage is a state or situation in which an actor connects otherwise unconnected actors or fills gaps or network holes in the social structure (Burt, 1992; Gould & Fernandez, 1989). Additionally, Brokerage is defined as connecting two separate areas of a network, and this concept has practical applications for cooperative Extension. Extension educators can identify where gaps exist in the outreach of Extension and which stakeholders are filling or able to fill these gaps (https://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/publication/WC197). From the given sample, we can infer that China, Chile, Russian Federation, USA, Germany, Rep.of Korea, and interestingly India can play the role of the coordinator broker in the trade network. For the given sample, Germany has the highest closeness centrality of 0.84 followed very closely by China and USA to other nations in the network.

Betweeness centrality

This centrality measure helps find the node that lies maximum number of times on multiple shortest paths (geodesics) among other nodes. So it tells us which node or nodes in the network are acting as brokers in the network. From the output below we can infer that Germany, USA, China, Russian Federation, and Japan play the role of a brokers between many trading nations.

hide 
E(net.ig)$weight <- 2**((E(net.ig)$weight - min(E(net.ig)$weight)) / diff(range(E(net.ig)$weight)))

Network Constraint

Constraint examines dependence upon network connections. It is a measure to assess the extent to which and actors behaviour is constrained by other actors in the network. In the given network Italy has the highest constraint followed by Brunei Darussalam, and Georgia.

Authority

Authorities are those actors in the network which get many incoming links from hubs, presumably because of their high quality relevant information. In this trade network Russian Federation has the highest authority score. This means that it would be closely linked to hubs such as China, USA, Chile, etc.

hide

Bridge

Bridges connects two different groups in the network. In the given trade network there are 18 bridges. From the network it can be observed that Turkmenistan, Djibouti, and Burkina Faso have low reflected centrality while the derived centrality is high,which makes them bridges to open newer opportunities of trade for copper.

Structural Equivalence & Block Models

Two nodes are said to be exactly structurally equivalent if they have the same relationships to all other nodes. So two actors must be exactly substitutable in order to be structurally equivalent. Two actors may be said to be structurally equivalent, if they have the same patterns of ties with other actors. However, in reality it is too challenging to have two actors with exact equivalence. In order to create clusters, complete linkage method has been used for hierarchical clustering to examine the clusters. As the data has been collected basis the top copper producing nations, the results of clustering are expected to be reflecting the top producer nations as single clusters basis the dollar value of trade they do, however, not for all. Blockmodels have been used to inspect the goodness of fit of the partitions that result from the clustering. After creating clusters, they have been tested using blockmodels. Basis the dendrogram and blocks generated through the network, we can observe that there are 4 distinct clusters emerging basis the trading pattern.

hide 
trade.se<-equiv.clust(matrix, equiv.fun="sedist", cluster.method = "complete", method="hamming",mode="graph")

summary(trade.se)


               Length Class  Mode     

cluster          7    hclust list

cluster.method   1    -none- character

glabels        205    -none- character

plabels        205    -none- character
hide 
plot(trade.se, labels=trade.se$glabels, cex = 0.5)

rect.hclust(trade.se$cluster,k=4)

From the dendrogram we can observe that China, Chile, and Japan are very different than the rest of 202 countries in exporting copper as they are large copper producing nations. Hence, they form individual clusters. USA and Peru are then very similar in behaviour of trade. Next to them is Germany. There is a lot of trade similarity between the cluster of Spain, Korea, India and cluster of Mexico, Australia, and Canada. The rest of the countries seems to be very similar in trade pattern as they form part of once cluster. However, if we further granularize the countries in various clsuters, more patterns can emerge.

blk.se<-equiv.clust(network.stat, equiv.fun="sedist", method="hamming",mode="graph")



#blockmodel and select partitions

blk2_mod<-blockmodel(network.stat,blk.se,k=2)



plot.block <- function(x = blk_copper_model, main = NULL, cex.lab =1){

  plot.sociomatrix(x$blocked.data, labels = list(x$plabels,x$plabels),

                   main = main, drawlines = FALSE, cex.lab = cex.lab)

  for (i in 2: length(x$plabels)) if (x$block.membership[i] != 

                                      x$block.membership[i-1])

    abline(v = i - 0.5, h = i - 0.5, lty = 3, xpd = FALSE)

}



plot.block(blk2_mod, main = "Copper Trade Network Partitions by 2",cex = 0.20)

plot(trade.wt, net.ig, vertex.label=NA, main = "Copper Trade Network Community Detection - Walktrap Method")

hide 
modularity(cluster_fast_greedy(net.ig.undirected))


[1] 0.1516442
hide 
modularity(trade.wt)


[1] 0.002815393

From the plots above we can observe that with fast greedy method we are getting 4 community partitions and with walktrap method with 10 or 20 or 100 steps, we just get one whole community out of the complete network. As per the modularity score of (0.17) fast greedy method as compared to the score (0.003) walktrap method. However, partitions cannot be just compared basis modularity.

hide 
compare.algs<-function(alg.a,alg.b,compare.meth=c("vi", "nmi", "split.join", "rand", "adjusted.rand")){

  #create list of community objects and methods

  comm.compare<-expand.grid(alg.a=alg.a, alg.b=alg.b, meth=compare.meth, result=NA, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

  #compare community partitions using a loop

for(i in 1:nrow(comm.compare)){

  comm1<-get(comm.compare$alg.a[i])

  comm2<-get(comm.compare$alg.b[i])

  method<-comm.compare$meth[i]

  comm.compare$result[i]<-compare(comm1, comm2, method)

}

  return(comm.compare)

}
hide 
#compare community partitions

trade.fg <- cluster_fast_greedy(net.ig.undirected)

compare.algs(alg.a=c("trade.fg"),alg.b="trade.wt")


     alg.a    alg.b          meth       result

1 trade.fg trade.wt            vi 1.097578e+00

2 trade.fg trade.wt           nmi 0.000000e+00

3 trade.fg trade.wt    split.join 1.340000e+02

4 trade.fg trade.wt          rand 3.307508e-01

5 trade.fg trade.wt adjusted.rand 8.294542e-17

Basis the slit.join score (1.340000e+02), we can conclude that the resulting partitions are less similar to each other. Rand Index indicates that the proportion of times that the two partitioning methods agree that two nodes belong in the same community is about 0.331.

Leading Label Propogation

Label propagation is a fast algorithm that uses neighborhood voting to find communities. It uses weighted networks if there is a weight edge attribute. On comparing the fast greedy method, walktrap method, and leading label propagation method, we can observe that the label propagation method gives very similar results as the fast greedy method, with the exception that one community is the largest in leading label propagation method. Hence, we can claim that there are different communities forming in the copper trade network. It would be interesting to study in the future how these communities have evolved ober time.

hide 
#Run clustering algorithm: leading label

trade.lab<-label.propagation.community(net.ig)

#Inspect community membership

igraph::groups(trade.lab)

Edge Betweeness Community

Edge betweenness looks for communities with sparse connections between them and works by eliminating high betweeness nodes. It uses weighted networks if we have a weight edge attribute or uses the options weights=. The algorithm automatically adjusts betweenness scores for directed networks, although this can be adjusted by setting the option directed=FALSE.

hide 
#Run clustering algorithm: edge betweenness

trade.edge<-label.propagation.community(net.ig)





#Inspect community membership

igraph::groups(trade.edge)
